The user's previous self-description is as follows: I now especially favor records with raspy, charismatic front‑and‑center vocals and career‑spanning, well‑curated sequencing that still feels energetic — compilations that preserve an artist’s grit and vocal personality are welcome. I like warm, analog‑colored remasters that preserve transient punch, micro‑dynamics and clear separation; tactile midrange with punchy, controlled drums; restrained reverb; tasteful keys and stacked harmonies naturally embedded in the mix.
From my earlier tastes I keep a love of tape‑warm, midrange‑forward rock; intimate close‑mic lead vocals; darker, guitar‑forward midrange crunch; tight, driving bass and drums; transparent, dynamics‑preserving mastering; economical, song‑serving solos; tasteful multitrack vocal overdubs; tape coloration and analogue bite; spacious imaging and collector‑grade packaging.
I dislike over‑slick or hyper‑bright masters; remasters that smear detail or flatten micro‑dynamics; loose, non‑curated compilations that blur into sameness; syrupy/cozy treatments; over‑layered sing‑along pop gloss; and horn/organ textures that strip raw rock immediacy.

